# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1873-spanish-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] General elections to the special Cortes of Cádiz were held in Spain in 1810.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 276 seats in the Cortes of Cádiz – which served as a parliamentary Regency after Ferdinand VII was deposed by Napoleon.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] During the first years of the Spanish War of Independence (1808-1814) the popular revolts of the Spanish people were accompanied by the creation of provincial and local defense "Juntas".
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] Those juntas assumed national sovereignty, forming their own local and regional governing bodies.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] These juntas aimed to defend against the French invasion and fill the power vacuum, refusing to recognize José I Bonaparte as their legitimate king.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The juntas were mainly composed of military personnel, representatives of the high clergy, officials and professors.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] In September 1808 the local and provincial juntas ceded their power to the Supreme Central Government Junta of the Kingdom, which led the war against the French and was recognized as the legitimate government of Spain by the United Kingdom and other anti-Napoleonic countries.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Supreme Junta summoned an extraordinary meeting of the Cortes of Cádiz, a revolutionary act, since the right to call for a meeting of the Cortes was exclusive to the crown.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] After an intense debate in the Supreme Junta it was decided that the Cortes of Cádiz would be unicameral, elected by census suffrage (only those with a certain level of income could vote) and indirect.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Cortes met for the first time in the last major Spanish foothold during the Peninsular War, Cádiz, on the Isla de León, on September 24, 1810.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 32 multi-member constituencies and 2 single-member constituencies.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] All male citizens above 25 years old could vote or be voted.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1813.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 149 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] The 1813 elections were the first ones held since the approval of the 1812 Cádiz Constitution.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] All males over 21 years old, a total of 3,216,460 people, had the right to vote.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1820.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 203 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The 1820 elections were the first ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Constitution of 1812.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 33 multi-member constituencies and various single-member ones.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] Most MPs were liberals, mainly from the *moderate* (or *doceañista*) faction.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1822.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] The 1822 elections were the second ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] 3,215,460 people were eligible to vote (universal male suffrage), out of a population of 11,661,865.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] Almost all MPs were liberals, mainly from the radical *veinteañista* or *exaltada* faction.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1834.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 188 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The 1834 elections were the first ones since 1822 and signalled the return of liberalism to Spain after the absolutist Década Ominosa.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Royal Statute of 1834, not under a full constitutional system.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] A first-past-the-post system was used with 48 multi-member constituencies and one single-member constituency.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] Only around 18,000 people were allowed to vote, out of a population of 12 million.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in November 1837.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 241 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 262,000 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] The elections were held on 22 September, at the peak of the First Carlist War.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 51 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain on 24 July 1839.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 376,255 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 48 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] A general election was held in Spain from 10 to 13 May 1873 to elect the members of the Constituent Cortes in the First Spanish Republic.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] 406 of 424 seats in the Cortes were up for election.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The election in Cuba was indefinitely postponed.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The election was held with universal male suffrage.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] It was held in very unorthodox conditions and drew a very low voter turnout, as neither the Carlist or Alfonsist monarchists participated.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The same happened with centralist and unitarian Republicans, or even the incipient labor organizations affiliated with the First International, who held a campaign of election boycott.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] This left the republic with a serious lack of legitimacy.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The Federal Democratic Republican Party won the election.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] As a consequence, the Spanish Cortes, reconstituted into a National Assembly in joint and permanent session, proclaimed the First Spanish Republic.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Under the 1873 Republic proclamation, the Spanish Cortes conceived in the 1869 Constitution were reassembled as a National Assembly in a joint session of both the Congress of Deputies and the Senate.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The electoral and procedural rules of the Democratic Sexennium remained in force with amendments, including the Senate's abolition and the Congress's conversion into a constituent assembly.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Election day was held over several voting days: the first was used to elect polling station officials, and the remaining ones were devoted to the parliamentary election itself.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The election to the Constituent Cortes was officially called on 11 March 1873, with the corresponding decree setting election day for between 10 and 13 May.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] In Cuba, elections were indefinitely postponed due to the Ten Years' War.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Voting for the Cortes was based on universal manhood suffrage, comprising all Spanish national males over 21 years of age with full civil rights.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] In Puerto Rico, voting was based on censitary suffrage, comprising Spanish males of voting age who were either literate or taxpayers for any direct tax, barring freedmen without political rights.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Additional restrictions excluded those deprived of political rights or barred from public office by a final sentence, criminally imprisoned (without bail) or convicted, and homeless.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The Constituent Cortes had one seat per 40,000 inhabitants or fraction above 20,000.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] All were elected in single-member districts using plurality voting and distributed among the provinces of Spain according to population.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Cuba and Puerto Rico were allocated 18 and 15 seats, respectively.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] As a result of the aforementioned allocation, 424 single-member districts were established.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] The law provided for by-elections to fill vacant seats during the legislative term.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Spanish males with the right to vote could run for election.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Causes of ineligibility applied to a number of territorial officials within their areas of jurisdiction or relevant territories, during their term of office and up to three months afterwards; public contractors; tax collectors; and public debtors.
[src:1873-spanish-general-election/1873-spanish-general-election] Additionally in Puerto Rico, ineligibility extended to those convicted of slave trade crimes.
